segments.text: But the numbers were still real small at 28,000 during that time frame, just as the numbers were small with regard to blacks and all those things.
As you became involved, who did you get early on?
Did someone help you get?
assigned as a student body government assistant or anything?
No, because I jumped right into it.
I jumped right into it because that fall of my freshman year, fall of 1973, I ran for, I immediately ran for
a freshman class senator from the College of Agriculture.
So I kind of never was a fish aid or none of that kind of stuff.
I really never served a full term as a senator.
I mean, I never did.
Some of the student body leaders were encouraged through Wayne Stark and the MSC.
Others were core.
So you're part of another group.
Yes.
And there were some things in place, actually,
except they didn't come into play until I served as student vice president, but there were some things in place that encouraged cross-pollinization between and amongst those organizations.
You know, they've got, oh, I heard somebody mention that there are like 20,000 different leadership opportunities or whatever it is on campus now.
We had, really, during that time frame,
two, three, four, really four sort of major leadership opportunities.
One was student government.
At the time, it was organized a little bit differently from the way it is run now, and I'll get that in just a second.
Secondly was the Memorial Student Center that Wayne Stark ran and provided that opportunity for kids to lead.
And then there was Corps of Cadets, of course, which had always been a part of the routine.
And then there was the Residence Halls Association, which was an organization basically made up of kids living on campus.
Within that MSC hierarchy, there were other activities in which students could participate, whether it was a political forum or SCONA or, you know,

whatever, the opus, all of the various, very many positive, worldly kinds of things that I think Wayne Stark should be given a great deal of credit for bringing to our university, and also for giving kids an opportunity to participate, and of course, thanks to the folks who gave money to support it, like the Wiley Lecture Series, for example, but to bring those kinds of things to campus.
At the time, student government was organized in a fashion such that
The president, that each of the officers of, we really sort of had a mixed bag.
It really wasn't a separated government in terms of the traditional government sense.
People ran for president, people ran for one of the various vice presidents that were available.
One was academic affairs, one was finance, one was rules and regs, one was external affairs, and there was another one, and I cannot remember what they said.
Oh, student services.
Each of those people ran independently.
But ultimately, when those people were elected, they were automatically members of the Senate.
So each of those vice presidents served as members of the legislative voting body, with the exception of me, the president, who had a ex officio role but could not vote.
But there was this thing called the executive committee.
And the executive committee was made up of these five vice presidents.

none of whom ran together on a ticket, and this president, who did not have a vote, and the speaker, who was the elected individual from the Senate body, and the MSC president served as a member of the executive committee.
What I did when I became president was I included the court commander
as a member of the executive committee and expanded it in that fashion.
Now, by the same token, I served as a member of the MSC council, which was the governing body of the, so there was sort of like a swap out that occurred, but there was

A lot of, in fact, everybody who, ironically, the guy who served as MSC president at that time and other members of his council, the guy who was core commander at that time, were also members of the Senate, too.
So we generally loaded it up, and so you were engaged in two or three different activities, and there was a great...
A unifying, not a dividing up.
That is true.
Now we still had the, we still had the, you know, normal core non-reg kind of a deal.
Of course, percentage of the student body was declining.
And we still had that.
In fact, my race for student body president, I ran against a guy, a guy from the Corps of Cadets, and another guy who was a non-reg like myself.
won it on the first ballot.
We didn't have to worry about a runoff, which was kind of nice.
Describe your campaign.
My campaign, the guy who was sort of like my campaign chairman was a guy from Kenya who had previously been vice president of academic affairs, and his name was Rajesh Kent.
And Raj served as my campaign chairman, for whatever that meant.
And at that time, we had a limit on spending associated with the campaigns of $100.
And that allowed me just about enough money to print up some flyers.
And there were really sort of only three places on campus where you could put, which were places in which they would allow you to put campaign signs.
And so by the time I bought the plywood and the paint,
to do my sign over by Kruger Dunn, which caught all the guys and gals headed from the court area kind of toward the Animal Science Committee and then down toward the Engineering Department.
One over by Sabisa, which was kind of to catch the kids on the north side of campus, and one right by the MSC.
That $100 went away real fast.
We didn't have websites like the kids can do now, which I thought was quite interesting during one of the most recent student body president campaigns.
And Raj tried diligently to get me to go door to door and I did it one afternoon for about four doors and I said, I'm not going to do this.
I'm going to do what I can to get my message out and hopefully this is going to work.
And that was it.
And it did.
But a lot of it again.

I sort of lucked out in the sense that I had this constituency there that still there were tons of kids who came from agricultural backgrounds or who lived in towns that I'd been in their, you know, Temple High School, speaking to a high school assembly or whatever from my FFA days.
And there were a lot of folks there that I knew or who knew of me.
And so I kind of got a cadre of individuals together like, would you please go talk for me at this collegiate FFA meeting or would you go talk for me at this
animal sciences, science, engineering society meeting and that was the summit substance of it.
It was pretty quick.
Do you think that all of your student activities had any effect on your grade point ratio?
No, none.
I kid the kids now because they talk about the reason it's taking five and a half, six years to get out of school.
I'm on your side on that one.
Because there's just so many student activities in which they can be involved in.
And their involvement in them, they just don't have time.
So therefore, they take 12 hours a semester.
There was not a single semester during my very short time when we started counting up months at Texas A&M.
There was not a single semester where I took less than a full load.
And I considered a full load at least 16 hours.
My last semester as an undergraduate, I took 22 hours and got a 4-0.
And the same was the case with my one semester in graduate school, where I took 12 hours, which is a full load from a graduate student perspective.
And I managed to balance all of that with the seemingly interminable meetings that arose as a result
of my activities as a student leader.
At the time, too, there were a lot of other roles.
It wasn't just going to a Senate meeting every other week, or it wasn't going to an executive committee meeting every Sunday night, but it was also doing the MSC Council stuff.
And various and sundry ones of us, because of the leadership roles we had, were student representatives, voting student representatives, in fact.
on a number of the university committees.
For example, I served as a member of the academic council.
Our vice president from rules and regs served on the rules and regs committee for the university.
I also served on the athletic council.
So there were a number of other activities that were sort of automatic that came as a result of the leadership roles that we occupied.
But in the final analysis, the impact that they had on my grades was kind of zero.
Let's see.
Back to the student routine.
What was your normal dress for class?
What did you normally wear to class?
My normal dress for class was blue jeans and even a no collared or a sometimes collared shirt.
I wore boots a lot.
I wore tennis a lot.
There were days that my dress was different because of the fact that
I might have other activities to do during the day that require a coat and tie.
For example, some luncheon or some speech or representing a student body in some capacity.
But that was more toward my last year on campus.
Otherwise, it was pretty student-oriented.
Of course, in the summer and a half that I went to summer school, it was shorts and t-shirts kind of a deal.
Throughout all this, too, I was also involved with singing cadets.
And so there were some times when that required my dress to be different.
Let's do the singing cadets.
Bob Boone was a conductor.
Again, a very, very weird experience for me.
I auditioned for the singing cadets in the fall of 1973 when I finally started my freshman year in earnest and was a bufo, which
name given to a first-year member of the same cadet, which is a term that comes from the comic opera.
And, you know, you had to wear a key, a wooden key, and you had to go get signatures and, you know, drop handles, look out.

In fact, this was probably the closest to the Corps in terms of some of the traditions associated with the Corps that I got was because of my Senate cadet involvement, which the Senate cadets had sort of appropriated.
And there were several members, I guess at the time probably 15 or 20% of the guys were also in the Corps of Cadets.
And so that sort of worked real well.
But then I dropped out.
And so I missed that experience.
Indeed, I missed going, I think that was the summer, I think 74 was the summer that the Singh Cadets went to Romania.
And I missed going to Romania because I was off playing at the Fayetteville.
came back and had to be a Bufo again in the fall of 1974.
And I continued to, as a member singer, that's the 74, 75 still year.
And I guess I did 75, 76.
And when I was elected student body president, I dropped out of the room, because that was just going to be too much time.
But Bob Boone was the rector.
Let's see.
There's another piece I want to throw into, which may or may not be sort of relevant to what you're thinking about.
When you ask me about dress, when I initially started in the fall of 1973, I lived on campus, as I had done that summer session before when I lived in McInnis.
And then I dropped out for a year, and because of sort of the way
I sort of got back into school the fall of 74.
I lived off campus with some friends in the fall of 74 and moved back on campus to McInnis again in the spring of 75.
I lived there for, I guess, another year.

So living on campus had a lot to do with dress as well because if you needed to go change during the course of the day, it was easy to run back over to the north side of campus and take that change if you needed to.
It became a little bit more difficult once I moved off campus again, which I did, I guess, the fall of 75.
I'm guessing now that in your day, people didn't yet have backpacks.
You're right.
Now that I think about that, you kind of had to carry them under your arm.
I don't remember ever having a backpack.

I don't know what we did when it rained, because it always used to rain on Tuesdays and Thursdays at about 1.45 in the afternoon when I had to walk from the engineering building to the academic building.
I remember those days pretty clearly.
I don't know what we did.
And y'all didn't wear shaggy, deliberately worn-out jeans yet.
No, but you'd wear some faded ones because it was just tons of washing, but it would be sort of equally faded.
But it was not with big holes in the knees.
No, no.
And no sandals yet.
No sandals.
Well, but not a whole lot.
And most people still had a haircut and still shaved.
Now, wait a minute.
No, no, no, no, wait a minute.
That's how one wants to describe that.
I had an afro during that time frame, which was sort of like the going...
In fact, there is a picture, which I'm most ashamed of, of the student leaders that we took.
I guess this was when I was, was it when I was a speaker or when I was president, I can't remember.
And we took it, the fountain was off, of course, but in the fountain between the Board of Regents annex and the main part of the MSC, there on the south end.
In fact, every time I walk by there and I think about that gross picture,
that are varying heights that water normally cascades over.
We were kind of standing and sitting there.
And I've got this huge afro.
I'm wearing it.
polyester leisure suit jacket.
Now this would have been when you were...
It was like 75.
You're not yet president of the student body.
No, it's a student leader picture.
And I can't remember whether it was when I was speaker and it's in the 75 Aggieland or whether or not it's in the 76.
Doesn't really make a difference.
Guys have long hair.
Some of the other student leaders have.
Some of the other student leader guys have long hair.
I've got long hair.
We're not polyester finest.
And I would have had, when I came to, well, I would have had a mustache, but for the fact that I was in St. Cadets.
And facial hair was not permitted in St. Cadets.
But I'm pretty, well, I'm not sure.
I have to go back and look.
But I'm pretty sure that I would be willing to bet you that when I got out of St. Cadets, I would have had a mustache go back, which I've had since then.
One of the questions I've enjoyed asking, please recall some of the jokes, pranks, and other good bull that you may have known about during your years at A&M.
If you start down that path, oh, let me see.
There were so many, it's kind of hard to... Well, share some of them.
I'll share one of them.
There was a...
I know of a guy who used to live in McInnis who was a pre-med student.
He's now a physician.
And for some reason he managed to get back to his room with various pieces of equipment from the chemistry labs that he was involved in, primarily plastic tubing, which somehow created a

nice set of materials that aided in the creation of a catapult type mechanism which could be used against aggressively against individuals who happen to park in the lot outside of Schumacher particularly when various fruits and vegetables were retrieved from Savisa during mealtimes

that were stored behind the tiles in the ceiling in the event that a certain residence hall person came by to look for any culprits associated with those activities flying off the fourth stoop of McKinnis.
That's one that always sticks out pretty much.
I'll have to think about some others.

You know, I, or like the night that a bunch of things that we were sort of forced by a member of the Board of Regents to go sing during the middle of the week, sing cadets, to go sing in Wortham, Texas.
And none of us wanted to do it, not a single one of us.
And we were kind of angry because some board member had beveled enough to force us to do that.
which, by the way, has a great deal to do with my attitude.
I was able to live with four regions now.
And I remember returning home.
I lived in an apartment during that time frame, so I was in the back of an apartment complex.
I remember returning home and seeing police cars about 12.30 at night at my apartment.
There had been an altercation between a roommate of mine and a young lady, and

Uh, when the police came by to talk to my roommate, uh, they walked into our apartment and noticed that it was decorated in early road sign and contained items that had once existed in the commons area.
Which various of my roommates had collected over the years.
Uh, they didn't have too much problem with the ones that, you know, Gawock Creek or, or
Brazos River, it was the stops and the yield signs in the one way that didn't sit too kindly with the college station police.
Another one of those points, fortunately, that a better judgment prevailed.
Alright, do you remember any played on you?
No, I actually avoided them.
I avoided them pretty well.
I was nice to everybody, so nobody ever played me.
I kept getting threatened by my buddies in the court if they were going to quad me, just for a good bowl.
So the student body president didn't get it?
This is when I was student body president, yeah.
They kept threatening that they were going to quad me, and what I did to overcome that was, and this is really sort of, I think, another one of the reasons that I was elected student body president.
During the time that I was a junior, or whatever is equivalent to my junior year, I guess,
when I was Speaker.
And I continued this actually throughout my time as a senior.
A number of the guys on CORE's staff were good friends of mine, or had become good friends of mine.
And, you know, so like, I guess Dunkin' wasn't open, Sabisa wasn't open on Sunday night, CORE used to go, or you had to go find someplace else to eat if you didn't live in an apartment or something.
There weren't just a whole hell of a lot of restaurants to choose one from.
In fact, one of our favorites,
because I'd just go join up the Corps guys on Sunday night and we'd go in or something, or a number of them.
And one of our favorites was the Rockies, which at that time was located down this dirt road in the middle of the woods, which I think is now about the location of the Albertsons, or thereabouts.
And I mean, there just weren't a whole lot of choices of places to go, but we did that sort of regularly.
What was the name of it?
Jose?
Did he operate?
I can't remember who operated.
I can't remember the name.
But that was sort of like a Sunday night ritual.
And so they really never did me in, which I looked at.
If you and your buddies were going to go partying.
Partying?
Yeah.
On a Saturday night?
No, Thursday night was a big one.
Oh, Thursday night?
Where?
It was Thursday and Saturday.
Back then and now, and I guess really this is something which I've learned since, it's really sort of a big night for partying, if you will, on college campuses all throughout the country.
But Thursday night was a big night for Lakey, for guys who wanted to go country and western dances.
I never sat, ironically, as much of a country and western fan as I am, and much of an agricultural background.
I have never to this day sat for Lakey.
But a lot of my buddies did it a very long time ago.
The other place was at the western, you know, eastern entrance to campus, the Magnum trips.
God, I can't believe I can't remember the name of this place.
It's set on the right hand side.
Eastgate?
Yeah, on Eastgate.
Right as you come out from the system administration building.
I'll try to remember the name of it.
But that was the big hangout.
A lot of Corps guys hung out there.

Um, there was a thing open for a while called the Sports Club, which is sort of where the athletes hung out, which is at Northgate, uh, sort of near the International House of Painters, and it was the last thing in that little shopping center there.

And then during the time that I was in school, 1974, um, the Dixie Chicken opened, which is great for those of us who lived on the north side of campus because you sort of walk across the street and do your deal and stumble back.
There was another thing going on in campus during this time too.
When I started school in July of 73, it was the first year that 18-year-olds were allowed to join the constitutional amendment that had passed.
And so that sort of changed the nature of it too because of the ability to go
to various places around town because of the change of the 18 year old.
It was no longer a forbidden.
It was no longer a forbidden place, and that's probably one of the reasons that Don opened the chicken right there across from campus, as did some other things that opened later on.
I do not think as well, let me add to this, I do not remember yet
Being a time frame, however, where I would say that kids drank to excess, I think it was fairly responsible.
And if they were drinking, what beverages were they drinking?
Beer.
It was basically beer.
And you could get mixed drinks over at the sports club.
And then there was a joint on Welbert Highway, the name of which I cannot remember, but that was sort of where
kind of rock kids hung out.
I mean, people kind of went to their places.
Uncle Ed's Hard Liquors was gone, wasn't it?
Uncle Ed's wasn't there.
No, that was not there.
What about Whiskey Bridge?
Whiskey Bridge wasn't there.
That building has now been leveled, by the way.
Yeah, no, that wasn't there.
God, I can't believe I can't remember the name of the place outside the system building.
I will remember, because I had a very, very, very
public incident there when I was student body president that will forever stick in my memory.
That was, I chalk it up to being the only negative known racial incident known to me.
Oh.
Racial incident that I was ever exposed to during my time in college.
Would you share that?
I will, and I wish I could think of the name of the place, which is
That's what's amazing.
I can't remember.
It was a pizza place.
Oh, gosh.
It has more poignancy if I can remember the name of it.
I can't remember the name of it.
Anyway, it was the year that I was student vice president.
It was after the Rice A&M football game.
And I think we won.
I believe so.
And I had gone in and was meeting some student government and other corps buddies.
There was a big corps hanging out there.
Those guys hung out a lot there.
And I was sitting back in the back of the bar with some friends and this person who was a friend or an acquaintance of mine.
Put him in the acquaintance category from that day forward.
who was also a student leader on campus.
And I won't go any further than that because it is probably, it only takes one more identifier and we'll know who that person is.
Ironically in the room too, this is really kind of a strange story, but ironically in the bar as well was a friend of mine, in fact probably the first person that I met on campus.
When I came there, his son was 73.
He also knew this individual very well.
And the individual walks in the door.
It's not called Charlie's, but what was the name of the place?
I'm going to ask.
God, I can't believe I can't remember.
We'll think of it.
We'll think of it.
He walks in the door, swings over the door, spies me in the back of the room.
In fact, I probably wasn't the only black person in the room.
And he yells at the very top of his lungs, above the den of the crowd, oh my God, look at the nigger, he's here.
And he just sort of kept saying that.
And he obviously had been drinking in excess.
And I, which he sort of had a problem with,
And I was trying to figure out how to respond to it, if at all.

And ironically, this guy who was one of the first persons, people that I met on campus, whom I heard on many other occasions, utter racial epithets about people who were other than black people, who just hears this person say this,
and heads toward the door where this individual came in, grabbed him by his shirt collar, slammed him up against the wall, and basically said, told him, shut up.
And if he ever said that again, particularly in an environment like that, he's going to beat the crap out of him.
And this friend was big enough to do that, and angry enough to do that.
And fortunately, I didn't have to do anything.
And I probably knew 90% of the people in the bar very well, first names.

You know, I could see the next day if I had responded in some different fashion than both the Brian Eagle and the battalion that had a wonderful story about the student vice president getting into a fight at this bar, the name of which I cannot remember what it is right now.
That was really the only incident that I was aware of that I ever dealt with any sort of racial problem during my time there.
My suspicion, too, is that during that time, there might have been 100, maybe 150 black kids on campus out of 28,000.
80% of them were athletes.

The rest of us came there because of either parents in the military and they decided they wanted to be in the Corps and they, too, wanted to be in the military, or there were people who came from the immediate
geographical area like Snook or Bryan or Caldwell or that sort of, or Hempstead.
Or others of us who came there for special educational programs like engineering or political culture.
Was there a special person that minority students turned to for advice and counsel?
There was no, there was no, there was nobody who served in that capacity.
Did
Did they need to be?
Did all these minority students get good advising?
I think as a practical matter, yeah, we all got great advising.
And I think that goes back more, Haskell, to the question of that thing that I talked about earlier in terms of the relationships between students.
